caption:

Say üëã to Seung Ju Kim (19), a BA student Psychology at the UvA. In her podcast @voiced_vulnerabilities she talks about mental health and shares her personal experiences with it.

üí≠ Seung Ju Kim: ‚ÄúAfter moving to a new country and transitioning into university, I‚Äôve struggled a lot with mental health and loneliness. I knew that I wasn‚Äôt the only one - I couldn‚Äôt be; and I‚Äôve always been keen on bringing more awareness around it. I love podcasts and how soothing they are to listen to, and I thought it was a great idea to start my own to raise more awareness for mental health. What I hope for the podcast is to provide a safe space for others to open up since you‚Äôre never alone in feeling like this. I experienced that the podcast allows others to be able to address their struggles and I‚Äôd love to see more people know that it‚Äôs normal to talk about it.‚Äù 

Visit the link in bio to find your way to the podcast üé∂

UPDATE #coronavirus ‚ùó The end of the academic year is approaching, and so we look ahead to the new academic year - a year in which education will once again take place on campus. Expectations are that the circumstances towards the end of August will allow for that. We are, of course, hopeful and optimistic.
üîπThe Ministry of Education, Culture and Science has formulated a ‚Äúbase scenario‚Äù (in Dutch) and the OMT will issue a definitive recommendation in early July. As it currently stands, expectations for the new academic year are that higher education institutions will be allowed to open their doors, social distancing will no longer be required, and voluntary self-tests will remain available for those who are not vaccinated. 
üîπFace masks will likely remain compulsory while walking through the buildings, however, and we are currently operating under the assumption that lectures will be subject to a maximum of 75 persons starting from September. Naturally, we hope that this restriction will also be lifted.
üîπThe UvA‚Äôs focus is on a return to on-campus education and being able to meet each other.  For students, that means that from September on, lectures will once again require you to be present in Amsterdam. The normal attendance requirements will be in effect. This also applies to foreign students. Only in special cases, e.g. for foreign students who are unable to attend due to international travel restrictions, programmes may explore additional solutions to enable students to receive education. 
üîπThe decision to ‚Äúreturn to normal‚Äù education is based on current developments. While we remain optimistic, we are also taking into account less ideal scenarios in which we have to (partly or temporarily) revert to online education. 
üîπRead more about lectures, exams, vaccinations and self-testing in the update via the link in bio or in our stories

title: ‚û°Ô∏èJoin our Pre-University Honours Programmes
caption:
üëâDid you know that @amsterdamsummerprograms organises Pre-University Honours Programmes for motivated high school students (16+)? 
In the past years we have been welcoming highly motivated students from all over the world each summer for an intensive university experience. Over the course of two weeks, students undertake a series of seminars and lectures, delving into the heart of complex interdisciplinary academic topics. This year‚Äôs subject are Journalism, Sustainable Cities, Business, Identity Politics and International Relations. 
Highlights:
- Join our truly international classroom: connect with peers from all over the world. 
- Engage in highly interactive live-sessions in small groups of around 20 students.
- Receive extensive personal feedback on your assignments. 
- Enjoy a real university experience at an esteemed institution with experienced staff and lecturers.

Check our story for more infoüëÄ

Have you met our international student ambassadors? üëã They can help you with any questions about studying at the UvA and can share their experiences with you! Get to know them in today‚Äôs stories or via our link in bio! üòä

UPDATE #coronavirus‚ùó: The UvA student exchange programmes‚ÜîÔ∏è for the second semester have unfortunately been cancelled. This decision was based on safety, academic added value and feasibility considerationsü¶†. In May of this year, we already made the decision to cancel face-to-face student exchanges in the first semester and decide on the exchange programmes for the second semester in the autumn.
üîπStudents who cannot go abroad for an exchange have been contacted. We will consult with these students to consider possible alternatives. The options for these vary according to the particular student, faculty and partner university. They may include postponing the exchange; completing a minor, elective or project at the UvA; or taking online courses at a partner universityü§ù.
üîπThe Executive Board will decide whether or not to resume student exchanges in the first semester of the 2021-2022 academic year in the spring of 2021üå∏.

title: Professor Damiaan Denys wins Ig Nobel Prize
caption: Congratulations to professor Damiaan Denys @amsterdam_umc for winning the Ig Nobel Prize! üéâü•≥üéä The prize is awarded each year to research that makes people laugh at first, and then makes them think. Professor Denys' team researched and first labeled the term 'mysofonia', a condition in which specific sounds, such as sneazing or rustling of paper can lead to disgust or aggressionüò§. In this video, Damiaan Denys describes his research and how he came in contact with it üèÜ.

UPDATE #cybersecurity‚ùó
The Security and Operations Centre of the Amsterdam University of Applied Sciences (AUAS) and University of Amsterdam (UvA) have found that an unknown third party has gained access to the ICT environmentsüíª of the AUAS and the UvA. Measures are being taken to minimise the impact and to ensure that education and research can continue to take place unimpeded.
üî∏We are investigating which areas of our ICT environment are affected. To limit the impact on education and research as much as possible, we will proactively shut down certain systems for a short period of timeüï∞Ô∏è. While they are shut down, the systems and the information contained there will not be available. We understand that this is inconvenient and will try to limit it where possible. 
üî∏In the interests of the investigation we cannot share any background information or details about the scope of the attack. You can find the latest information on uva.nl or on services.uva.nl, including updates on any further consequences, and if applicable, what actions you can take ‚û°Ô∏è link in bio

Have you picked up any new hobbies during lockdown? üôã‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Meet Femke (Communication Science student) and her Corona hobby: making jewelry in part 6 of our hobby series. 

Femke: ‚ÄúAt the start of the pandemic, I started searching for a new offline hobby. My mom had many beads and tools from when she used to make her own jewelry back in the days. So, I decided to start making my own jewelry with her old stock. I really like that I can create the jewelry I love myself. And, I use vintage and recycled beads so that it has as little impact on the environment as possible üëè I love that this forces me to be creative with the beads that I can find.

Because of my hobby, I became good friends again with an old friend from high school. We hadn't spoken to each other for over two years but then she suddenly ordered some of my jewelry via Instagram. We got in touch again and now we're even making jewelry together üòÉ

To other students I want to say: enjoy the little things. During these times I try to look at what I do have, instead of what I don't have or what is not possible. Every day I think about the things I'm grateful for and these things then feel like little presents üéÅ It helps me experience positive vibes.‚Äù

üì∏ by @ilsoovandijk

üëã Meet Aleksandra and Simone! They‚Äôre part of @HeForShexUvA, a student association founded last year, which is focused on creating a discussion around (gender) equality. It is a student chapter of the UN global movement for gender equality, striving to include all genders in feminism.

Want to know more? Aleksandra and Simone are taking over our IG stories today! You can also visit @heforshexuva üëç

üëÄ Get a glimpse at your fellow UvA students‚Äô real life rooms in our photo series, ‚ÄòGluren bij de Buren‚Äô (ENG: A peek inside your neighbour‚Äôs house). This week we‚Äôre visiting Shirin‚Äôs room in the final part of our student housing photo series. She‚Äôs 20 years old and a BA student in Media and Culture from Munich (Germany). She got her room via UvA Housing. 

Shirin: "I was a bit anxious when I decided to go to Amsterdam and find a place on my own. It felt weird to go from being around my family all the time to live in a room alone. I feel very lucky to get a spot in student housing where all my roommates have the same vibes and energy as I do. We have a shared kitchen and hang out there (or in each other‚Äôs room) a lot. You‚Äôre never really alone here. 

üëâ My advice for international students who want to apply for UvA Housing: get an overview of the districts in Amsterdam and decide where you want to live. When the application opens, be quick and make sure you're on time. If you‚Äôre not applying via UvA Housing, be aware of Facebook scams. The whole process can sometimes be a little bit confusing but push through and never give up! I‚Äôm so happy I‚Äôm here now üòä‚Äù

Stats üìã

üëÄ Get a glimpse at your fellow UvA students‚Äô real life rooms in our photo series, ‚ÄòGluren bij de Buren‚Äô (ENG: A peek inside your neighbour‚Äôs house). This week we visit Abinash, an international student from India. He‚Äôs doing the Master‚Äôs programme in Computational Science at the UvA and arrived in Amsterdam only a few weeks ago üõ¨

Abinash (23): ‚ÄúI decided to come to Amsterdam in March because I wanted to interact with the people and market here. I applied for this room through UvA student housing. They told me to visit www.room.nl, which I did, and in this manner I found this room üè†

All the furniture came with the room. I wanted to add something old and something new to the room. The something new had to be something of the Netherlands. It became the posters on the wall and a book of the Royal Netherlands Steamship Company (KNSM) that I found via a guy from Facebook Marketplace that inherited the full collection of the KNSM. The something old had to be something that reminded me of India üáÆüá≥ It‚Äôs a small statue of Ganesh, the God of Wisdom.

It‚Äôs been great so far. I joined the Facebook group Citylife Amsterdam. It‚Äôs a community that helps me to get engaged with other people and Amsterdam. I hope that new students will join me there üòÉ‚Äù

Stats üóí
room: 28m2 studio | location: Carolina MacGillavrylaan flat (nearby Science Park) | price ‚Ç¨415 (thanks to housing allowance / huurtoeslag) | no roommates or shared facilities.

It‚Äôs International Women‚Äôs Day üôã‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è‚ú® In light of this important day, we want to introduce you to Heleen Kibbelaar. She‚Äôs a UvA PhD candidate in complex fluid systems (think of: toothpaste, shower gel, make-up) and studies this in the lab at Science Park. In 2017 she went to Togo (West-Africa) to develop sunscreen for people with albinism.

Heleen üí¨: ‚ÄúPeople with albinism do not have natural protection against UV rays. Sunscreen is therefore a very important and live saving protective utility for them, as it has proven to reduce the risks of skin cancer considerably. Regrettably, it‚Äôs almost impossible to obtain sunscreen in Togo and therefore I found it important to do something about this. Together with a company, I developed a sunscreen which could be locally and cost effective produced. Currently more than 600 people with albinism in Togo are provided with sunscreen and their health is monitored.‚Äù ‚òÄÔ∏è

üëÄ Want to know more about Heleen and the work she does, visit @uva_science for an in depth interview. Also, Heleens owns a popular IG account @sciencemeetscosmetics in which she explains the science behind beauty products. If you‚Äôre in need for some beauty advice, go take a look üíÑ

What makes a photo perfect? üì∏

You might think this is related to what can be seen on the picture. However, this is not true üò± Gijs Overgoor studied the picture perfect by studying the brain with the help of machine learning üß† He found out that it does not matter all that much what exactly can be seen on a photo. Your behavior has already been influenced before you have had a good look at what is on it. Based on its complexity, you decide whether or not to stop scrolling as you go through your Instagram timeline.

Want to read more about what makes a good Instagram photo? Visit the UvA Open House. At the #uvaopenhouse you can get to know our programmes through various themes. This week it‚Äôs all about the brain. Check our link in bio üëÄ
